Introduction</em>, Boulder: Westview Press.</li>

<li>Ayers, M., 1974. &ldquo;Individuals without sortals&rdquo;,
<em>Canadian Journal of Philosophy</em>, 4: 113&ndash;48.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1975. &ldquo;The ideas of power and
substance in Locke&rsquo;s philosophy&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical
Quarterly</em>, 25: 1&ndash;27. Reprinted in I. C. Tipton (ed.),
<em>Locke on Human Understanding</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press, 1977, 77&ndash;104.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1991a. &ldquo;Substance: prolegomena to a
realist theory of identity&rdquo;, <em>The Journal of Philosophy</em>,
88: 69&ndash;90.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1991b. <em>Locke</em> (Volume 2), London:
Routledge; Part I is titled &ldquo;Substance and mode&rdquo;.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1994. &ldquo;The foundations of knowledge
and the logic of substance: the structure of Locke&rsquo;s general
philosophy&rdquo;, in his <em>Locke&rsquo;s Philosophy: Content and
Context</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press, 49&ndash;73. Reprinted in
Chappell (1998), 24&ndash;47.</li>

<li>Barker, S. and Jago, M., 2018. &ldquo;Material objects and
essential bundle theory&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>,
175(12): 2969&ndash;2986.</li>

<li>Barnes, J., 1987. <em>Early Greek Philosophy</em>, Harmondsworth:
Penguin Books.</li>

<li>Bennett, J., 1966. <em>Kant&rsquo;s Analytic</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1971. <em>Locke, Berkeley, Hume</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1987. &ldquo;Substratum&rdquo;, <em>History
of Philosophy quarterly</em>, 4: 197&ndash;215. Reprinted in Chappell
(1998), 129&ndash;48.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2001. <em>Learning from Six Philosophers:
Descartes, Spinoza, Leibniz, Locke, Berkeley, Hume</em>, Oxford:
Clarendon Press. </li>

<li>Broackes, J., 2006. &ldquo;Substance&rdquo;, <em>Proceedings of the
Aristotelian Society</em>, 106(1): 133&ndash;68. </li>

<li>Chappell, V. (ed.), 1998. <em>Locke</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Chisholm, R., 1969. &ldquo;The observability of the self&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy and Phenomenological Research</em>, 31: 7&ndash;21;
reprinted in <em>Self-Knowledge</em>, Q. Cassam (ed.), Oxford: Oxford
University Press, 1994.</li>

<li>Crane, T. and Farkas, K. (eds.), 2004. <em>Metaphysics: a guide
and anthology</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press. (Part II,
&ldquo;Being&rdquo;, is especially relevant.)</li>

<li>Denkel, A., 1992. &ldquo;Substance Without Substratum&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy and Phenomenological Research</em>, 52(3):
705&ndash;11.</li>

<li>Descartes, R., <em>The Philosophical Writings of Descartes</em>,
trans. J. Cottingham, R. Stoothoff, D. Murdoch, Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press, 1985.</li>

<li>Druart, T., 1987. &ldquo;Substance in Arabic Philosophy:
Al-Farabi&rsquo;s Discussion&rdquo;, <em>Proceedings of the American
Catholic Philosophical Association</em>, 61: 88&ndash;97.</li>

<li>Dummett, M., 1987. &ldquo;The intelligibility of Eucharistic
doctrine&rdquo;, in <em>The Rationality of Religious Belief: essays in
honour of Basil Mitchell</em>, W. Abraham and S. Holzer (eds.),
Oxford: Clarendon Press, 231&ndash;61.</li>

<li>Fine, G., 1993. <em>On Ideas: Aristotle&rsquo;s Criticism of
Plato&rsquo;s Theory of Forms</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Fine, K., 1999. &ldquo;Things and their parts&rdquo;, <em>Midwest
Studies in Philosophy</em>, 23: 61&ndash;74.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2010. &ldquo;Towards a theory of
part&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Philosophy</em>, 107: 559&ndash;89.</li>

<li>Flemming, N., 1987. &ldquo;On Leibniz on subject and
substance&rdquo;, <em>The Philosophical Review</em>, 96: 69&ndash;95.
Reprinted in Woolhouse (1994), 104&ndash;27.</li>

<li>Gill, M. L., 1989. <em>Aristotle on Substance</em>, Princeton:
Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Gopnik, A., 2009. &ldquo;Could David Hume Have Known about
Buddhism? Charles Fran&ccedil;ois Dolu, the Royal College of La
Fl&egrave;che, and the Global Jesuit Intellectual Network&rdquo;,
<em>Hume Studies</em>, 35(1&ndash;2): 5&ndash;28.</li>

<li>Gorman, M., 2006. &ldquo;Independence and Substance&rdquo;,
<em>International Philosophical Quarterly</em>, 46(2): 147&ndash;59.
</li>

<li>Gotthelf, A., 1987. &ldquo;Aristotle&rsquo;s conception of final
causality&rdquo;, in A. Gotthelf and J. G. Lennox edd.,
<em>Philosophical Issues in Aristotle&rsquo;s Biology</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press, 204&ndash;42.</li>

<li>Graham, D. W., 1987. <em>Aristotle&rsquo;s Two Systems</em>,
Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Hawley, K., 2001. <em>How Things Persist</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Heidegger, M., 1927 [2008]. <em>Being and Time</em>, New York:
HarperPerennial.</li>

<li>Hoffman, J. and Rosenkranz, G. S., 1994. <em>Substance Among Other
Categories</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1997. <em>Substance: Its Nature and
Existence</em>, London: Routledge.</li>

<li>Hume, D., 1978. <em>A Treatise of Human Nature</em>, P. H.
Nidditch (ed.), Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Irwin, T., 1988. <em>Aristotle&rsquo;s First Principles</em>,
Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Jaworski, W., 2011. <em>Philosophy of Mind: a comprehensive
introduction</em>, Malden, MA: Wiley&ndash;Blackwell.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012. &ldquo;Powers, structures and
minds&rdquo;, in <em>Powers and Capacities in Philosophy: the New
Aristotelianism</em>, R. Groff and J. Greco (eds.), London: Routledge,
145&ndash;70.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016. <em>Structure and the Metaphysics of
Mind: how hylomorphism solves the mind-body problem</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Johnston, M., 2006. &ldquo;Hylomorphism&rdquo;, <em>Journal of
Philosophy</em>, 103: 652&ndash;98.</li>

<li>Kant, I., <em>The Critique of Pure Reason</em>, trans. N.
Kemp-Smith, London: Macmillan, 1963.</li>

<li>Kim, J., 2005. <em>Physicalism, or Something Near Enough</em>,
Princeton: Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Koons, R. C., 2014. &ldquo;Staunch vs. Faint-hearted Hylomorphism:
Toward an Aristotelian Account of Composition&rdquo;, <em>Res
Philosophica</em>, 91(2): 151&ndash;77.</li>

<li>Koslicki, K., 2008. <em>The Structure of Objects</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018. <em>Form, Matter and Substance</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press. </li>

<li>Kripke, S., 1980. <em>Naming and Necessity</em>, Oxford:
Blackwell.</li>

<li>Lagerlund, H., 2012. &ldquo;Material substance&rdquo;, in <em>The
Oxford Handbook of Medieval Philosophy</em>, J. Marenbon (ed.), Oxfor:
Oxford University Press, 468&ndash;85.</li>

<li>Laycock, H., 2006. <em>Words Without Objects: semantics, ontology
and logic for non-singularity</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press.</li>

<li>Leibniz, G. W., &ldquo;Critical Thoughts on the General Part
of the Principles of Descartes&rdquo;, in G. W. Leibniz,
<em>Philosophical Papers and Letters</em>, 2nd edition, L. Loemker
(ed. and trans.), Alphen aan den Rijn: Kluwer, 1989.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, <em>Philosophical Texts</em>, R. S.
Woolhouse and R. Francks (trans. and eds.), Oxford: Oxford University
Press, 1998.</li>

<li>Lewis, D., 1986. <em>On the Plurality of Worlds</em>, Oxford:
Blackwell.</li>

<li>Lloyd, A. C., 1981. <em>Form and Universal in Aristotle</em>,
Liverpool: Francis Cairns.</li>

<li>Locke, J., 1997. <em>An Essay Concerning Human Understanding</em>,
R. Woolhouse (ed.), London: Penguin Books.</li>

<li>Lowe, J., 1998. <em>The Possibility of Metaphysics: substance,
identity and time</em>, Oxford: Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2006. <em>The Four-Category Ontology: a
